to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Gaynsford III was born about 1358, in Crowhurst, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Gaynsford II, was 23 and his mother, Cristina, was 19. He married Mrs. John Gaynsford about 1393, in Crowhurst, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1420, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1358–about 1420":"umbes 1358–umbes 1420","1358–1420":"1358–1420","–Female":"Surnud","1394–1450":"1394–1450","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1337–1358":"1337–1358","1341–1432":"1341–1432","about 1393":"umbes 1393","1341":"1341","1396":"1396","1450":"1450","1394":"1394","after 1358":"pärast 1358","Abt 1394":"umbes 1394","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1432":"1432","about 1358":"umbes 1358","1420":"1420","about 1420":"umbes 1420","about 1396":"umbes 1396","Crowhurst, Surrey, England":"Crowhurst, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Crowhurst, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Crowhurst, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Crowhurst, Surrey, England":"Crowhurst, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"